				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: What to do when you have a Shammy and Chanter in group?<a name="5848"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Mar 31 03 9:24 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Depending on level, can get away with 3 or 4 songs (depending on syour standard twist) for maximum output.  I'm 65, with a reasonably full song book and the common songs I twist are all PoP songs.  Psalm of Veeshan, Warsong of Zek, and Wind/Chorus of Marr with Rislona's getting popped in as well if I feel like it.  Yes, there are things in that which are allready covered, but there are reasons. 
<br />

<br />
Psalm of Veeshan and Warsong I use for DS's.  As has been said, its kinda hard to resist a DS, and those 2 get me to up about a 70 DS depending on what else I'm bothering to do.  The haste from warsong is full on redundant to me now, and would be for you, but the DS and atk are too good to ignore.
<br />

<br />
Veeshan I use purely for the DS, and for the wow factor as well when people notice their resists.  Rislona's I use for 2 reasons - the 30% stackable haste, and the + to casters nukage.  If the chanter is smart, they will only be buffing with VoG, SoV, or similar hastes that have stat buffs built in.  Rest of the haste the bard can still cover.  Manasong gets played for obvious reasons.
<br />

<br />
At sub 60 levels, can alter most of those songs with lower lev variations.  Warmth or Cooling instead of Veeshan, Rondo instead of warsong, and Vah Shir instead of Rislonas.  The options are there for the fighting bard.  Or just do DoT's and melee.  Still do a lot of DoT damage if you have your epic, and it adds a LOT to your DPS.
<br />

<br />
Can also make your own options up.  One thing I do occasionally in weaker groups is mez a mob as its dragged in to let the slowers debuff and slow without it being any problems to people.  With PoP mobs hitting for 600+ it's often a good call.  Or do as others have suggested and do the pulling.  Lull is a powerful tool.</span></td>
