				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">ROFL Eclyptic<a name="7428"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">May 19 03 12:04 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>From Eclyptic<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">You can always tell the difference between a well-played bard and a sloppily played bard.</span></blockquote>Group last night:
<br />
62 Bard
<br />
55 Ranger
<br />
60 Shaman
<br />
5? Monk
<br />
5? Wizard
<br />
5? Cleric
<br />

<br />
Soon as I pop into group I politely tell the shaman to unmem Celerity.  I politely tell the monk I will be pulling and search through my bags for some peri's for the cleric.
<br />

<br />
Shaman cheers.  Monk says Yay!  <b>Cleric says, Professional bards really do scare me.</b>
<br />

<br />
That cleric hit it right on the nose. We are professionals because we do our best to find situations in which we can contribute to the betterment of the group/raid.
<br />

<br />
And Eclyptic you are 100% correct.  A sloppily played bard sticks out like a sore thumb and will be still in Velks or Tier 1 while you are dropping gods in Time... maybe  <img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-5.gif" border="0" alt="Wink" hspace="2" /> HEY IT CAN HAPPEN!.
<br />

<br />
At the risk of sounding like I am blowing my own horn (/groan <img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-4.gif" border="0" alt="Tongue out" hspace="2" />) I forgot to mention this group called me to group and I didn't know any of them except the ranger whom I've grouped with several times.  I wasn't LFG.
<br />

<br />
For me, that doesn't happen all the time, but if you play your bard to the best of your abilities people will remember you as a bard that <u>is not sloppy</u>.
<br />

<br />
My song lineup in that situation:
<br />

<br />
<b>Warsong of Zek</b> - Haste/DS etc.
<br />
<b>Battlecry of the Vah'shir</b> - Haste Cap
<br />
<b>Wind of Marr </b> - Mana/Health
<br />
<b>Chant of the Plague</b> - For pulling
<br />
<b>Dreams of Thule</b> - CC (Always up)
<br />
<b>Charm or Kazumi's</b> - CC/Divine Aura (Kazumi's if uncharmable by me)
<br />
<b>Silent Song of Quellious</b> - Lull
<br />
<b>Selo's</b> - Training.. erm I mean escaping. (Always up)
<br />

<br />
Add Enchanter to group (I will melee):
<br />
Chant of the Plague
<br />
Chant of Poison
<br />
Chant of Frost
<br />
Wind of Marr
<br />
Dreams of Thule
<br />
Charm or Kazumi's
<br />
Quellious
<br />
Selo's
<br />

<br />
With my weapons I have around 30-35 DPS.  Add to that the dot damage of 33 DPS (no resists/missed notes and all active ((62+62+73)/6)) I do pretty good in melee.  Sure, the dot damage takes a little bit to ramp up due to cast times vut in fights lasting about 1-1.5 minutes it is tolerable.
<br />

<br />
But it is still (for me) more DPS over using my drum ((83+83+98)/6 = 44 DPS).
<br />

<br />
Granted,  this lineup and my whole theory may be flawed in more ways than one.  But it works for me and I have had no complaints... except when I DA the group by accident... DOH!</span></td>
